<bibRefCitation author="Aghmich" box="[1028,1281,1922,1949]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Aghmich" pageId="157" pageNumber="158" pagination="189 - 198" refId="ref130569" refString="Aghmich A., Taboada S., Toll L. &amp; Ballesteros M. 2016. First assessment of the rocky intertidal communities of Fildes Bay, King George Island (South Shetland Islands, Antarctica). Polar Biology 39: 189 - 198. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 00300 - 015 - 1814 - 9" type="journal article" year="2016">
Aghmich 
<emphasis box="[1149,1211,1922,1948]" italics="true" pageId="157" pageNumber="158">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
) and was found amidst macro-algae (
<bibRefCitation author="Richardson" box="[507,711,1961,1988]" firstAuthor="Richardson" pageId="157" pageNumber="158" refId="ref143937" refString="Richardson M. G. 1977. The ecology (including physiological aspects) of selected Antarctic marine invertebrates associated with inshore macrophytes: 1 - 137. PhD thesis, University of Durham, UK." type="book" year="1977">Richardson 1977</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Thurston" box="[730,920,1961,1988]" firstAuthor="Thurston" pageId="157" pageNumber="158" pagination="1 - 133" refId="ref145646" refString="Thurston M. H. 1972. The Crustacea Amphipoda of Signy Island, South Orkney Islands. British Antarctic Survey Scientific Reports 71: 1 - 133. Available from: http: // nora. nerc. ac. uk / 509215 / 1 / The % 20 crustacea % 20 amphipoda % 20 of % 20 Signy % 20 Island, % 20 South % 20 Orkney % 20 Islands % 20 - % 20 BAS % 20 Scientific % 20 Report % 2071. pdf [accessed 27 Sep. 2016]" type="journal article" year="1972">Thurston (1972)</bibRefCitation>
stated: “apparently associated with algae growing on rocks, boulder or gravel bottoms, 
<quantity box="[728,822,2000,2027]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" metricValueMax="15.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="157" pageNumber="158" unit="m" value="9.0" valueMax="15.0" valueMin="3.0">3–15 m</quantity>
